</li><li> In <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/AlfdisAndGunnora" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/AlfdisAndGunnora">Alfdis &amp; Gunnora</a></em>, both Gunnora and her friend Fulla wield pikes in the army.
</li><li> <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/BirdBoy" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/BirdBoy">Bird Boy</a></em>: <a class="urllink" href="http://bird-boy.com/volume-1-page-4">Bali is introduced lugging a lot of spears<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a>.
</li><li> The weapon of choice for Kiran of <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/Chirault" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/Chirault">Chirault</a></em>.
</li><li> In <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/ChampionsOfFaraus" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/ChampionsOfFaraus">Champions of Far'aus</a></em>, all of the city guards, no matter what city or country they're in, are equipped with spears.
</li><li> Carrot in <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/CucumberQuest" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/CucumberQuest">Cucumber Quest</a></em> had one...before he ran off in terror away from a harmless monster.
</li><li> The Polearm is the weapon of choice for two characters in <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/CwensQuest" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/CwensQuest">Cwen's Quest</a></em>. Firstly for the main character Cwen and secondly for Gram Trellion whom we will generously call both a <strike><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ChivalrousPervert" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ChivalrousPervert">Chivalrous Pervert</a></strike> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/HandsomeLech" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/HandsomeLech">Handsome Lech</a> &amp; probably <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FakeUltimateHero" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FakeUltimateHero">Fake Ultimate Hero</a> <a class="urllink" href="http://www.drunkduck.com/Cwens_Quest/index.php?p=424028">whom originally gave Cwen her's<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a>.
</li><li> In <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/Drowtales" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/Drowtales">Drowtales</a></em>, Vaelia uses this sort of weapon. After a 15 year <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Timeskip" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Timeskip">Timeskip</a> her charge Ariel seems to have taken it as her primary weapon, likely due to her influence.
</li><li> In <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/Endstone" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/Endstone">Endstone</a></em>, <a class="urllink" href="http://endstone.net/2010/07/08/4-04/">wolves use them to hunt Kyri<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a>.
</li><li> In <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/GirlGenius" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/GirlGenius">Girl Genius</a></em>, Oggie the Jaegermonster uses a triple-poleaxe. Mostly as a weapon, but also as a springboard for his <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PowerTrio" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PowerTrio">fellow Jaegers</a> to jump off and a pole-vault so he can follow them.
</li><li> Void in <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/LsEmpire" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/LsEmpire">L's Empire</a></em> started off with a spear and a shield. He later upgraded to having "Spear" as his <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SemanticSuperpower" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SemanticSuperpower">Semantic Superpower</a>.
</li><li> <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/MAGISA" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/MAGISA">MAG-ISA</a></em> &mdash; <a class="urllink" href="http://mag-isa.thecomicseries.com/comics/pl/119763">Chu's Weapon<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a>
</li><li> While he never manages to acquire one, Roy memorably attempted to purchase a polearm in <a class="urllink" href="http://www.giantitp.com/comics/oots0136.html">this<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a> <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/TheOrderOfTheStick" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/TheOrderOfTheStick">The Order of the Stick</a></em> strip.
<ul><li> "That Guy With A Halberd", a nameless Azure City <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RedShirt" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RedShirt">Red Shirt</a> with a rather rabid fan following.
</li><li> "<a class="urllink" href="http://www.giantitp.com/comics/oots0721.html">Sneak Attack on a stick, snake-face!!<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a>"
</li></ul></li><li> Angelika's weapon of choice in <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/OurLittleAdventure" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/OurLittleAdventure">Our Little Adventure</a></em>, though it's kind of subverted in that it's mostly for show. Her real weapon of choice is <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BlackMagicianGirl" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BlackMagicianGirl">magic.</a> She gets rid of it later for a magical morningstar.
</li><li> In <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/Polanstuck" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/Polanstuck">Polanstuck</a></em> Indonesia uses one.
</li><li> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BadassAdorable" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BadassAdorable">Madeline</a> the ditzy paladin from <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WebComic/RustyAndCo" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WebComic/RustyAndCo">Rusty and Co.</a></em> wields a <a class="urllink" href="http://rustyandco.com/comic/level2/level-2-3/">hoe<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a> she thinks is a Holy Avenger. And is still deadly with that.
<ul><li> She eventually <a class="urllink" href="http://rustyandco.com/comic/level-6-4/">upgraded<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a>. To a "vorpal halberd". Which looks unsurprisingly like a spade, of course. But works surprisingly like a vorpal halberd. When Madeline swings it with closed eyes, anyway.
</li></ul></li><li> <a class="urllink" href="http://www.samuraiprincess.com">Princess Raeka<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a> from <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/SamuraiPrincess" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/SamuraiPrincess">Samurai Princess</a></em> uses a naginata. A notable weapon for a female samurai.
</li><li> Spears of one variety or another are a weapon seen often enough in <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/SleeplessDomain" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/SleeplessDomain">Sleepless Domain</a>'s</em> Magical Girls that there have been at least two incarnations of "Team Spear" within two decades. Heartful Punch's mother was a member of the earlier incarnation as "Moonlight Spear". She wielded a naginata while her teammates, Sunlight Spear and Starlight Spear, used a halberd and guandao respectively.
</li><li> <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/SweetHome" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/SweetHome">Sweet Home</a></em>: Hyun's weapon is a broken mop handle with a knife attached to it. Dusik Hahn upgrades it to also conduct electricity.
</li><li> <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/Tamuran" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/Tamuran">Tamuran</a></em>: <a class="urllink" href="http://www.tamurancomic.com/?p=221">A guard's choice to harrass travelers<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a>.
</li><li> Haruna in <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/TsunamiChannel" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/TsunamiChannel">Tsunami Channel</a></em> has been shown to have a high proficiency in naginata, and she is quick to pop one from <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Hammerspace" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Hammerspace">Hammerspace</a> whenever she needs to use it. Strangely, this is used to point how much of a traditional <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/YamatoNadeshiko" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/YamatoNadeshiko">Yamato Nadeshiko</a> she is.
</li></ul></div>
